1.  
Data Structures and ADTs  
• What is an ADT? An Abstract Data Type (ADT) is a logical description of a data 
structure that specifies what operations can be performed (like push or pop) but not 
how they are implemented in code. 
• Stack Operations Complexity: Operations like push, pop, and peek are usually O(1) 
(constant time) because they only interact with the "top" of the data structure, 
regardless of how many elements are stored. 
