3.  
Recurrence & Paradigms Reflection  
• Binary Search (Divide & Conquer): This fits the paradigm because it divides the 
sorted array into two halves, ignores one, and "conquers" the remaining half. The 
recurrence is T(n) = T(n/2) + O(1) \Rightarrow O(\log n)$. 
• Memoized Fibonacci (Dynamic Programming): Memoization solves the "overlapping 
subproblems" issue where the naive version recalculates the same values thousands 
of times. By storing results, we reduce the complexity from exponential to linear. 
• Tower of Hanoi (Recursion): This uses the idea of moving $n-1$ disks as a smaller 
subproblem. The number of moves is 2^n - 1$ because each disk added doubles the 
previous work plus one extra move. 
4.  
Real-Life Examples  
• Divide & Conquer: Searching for a name in a physical dictionary by opening it in the 
middle and narrowing down the section. 
• Dynamic Programming: Using a GPS or Map app that remembers the shortest path 
to sub-destinations so it doesn't re-calculate the whole route every time you move. 
• Greedy: A cashier giving change using the fewest coins possible by always picking the 
largest denomination first.
